import pandas as pd

from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller, kpss
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Upload Excel files
print("Please upload COST 1min-2days interval Excel file")
short_upload = files.upload()
short_filename = list(short_upload.keys())[0]
short_df = pd.read_excel(short_filename)

print("Please upload COST 5min-5days interval Excel file")

long_filename = list(long_upload.keys())[0]

print("COST 5min-5days DataFrame columns:", list(long_df.columns))

# Extract closing prices using user-specified column name
try:

    long_close_full = long_df[close_column]    # Keep the full 5min-5days data

print(f"\nNumber of data points in COST 1min-2days (full): {len(short_close_full)}")
print(f"Number of data points in COST 5min-5days (full): {len(long_close_full)}")

# Store the original last value of the 1min-2days data from the Excel file
original_short_last_value = short_df[close_column].iloc[-1]
print(f"Original last value from COST 1min-2days Excel file: {original_short_last_value:.2f}")

# Data cleaning and preprocessing
def preprocess_series(series, name):
    print(f"\nPreprocessing {name}:")
    # Check for NaN or inf values
    nan_count = series.isna().sum()
    print(f"Number of NaN values in {name}: {nan_count}")
    inf_count = np.isinf(series).sum()
    print(f"Number of inf values in {name}: {inf_count}")

    # Replace inf with NaN
    series = series.replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)

    # Handle NaN values
    if series.isna().sum() > 0:
        print(f"Handling NaN values in {name}...")
        series = series.interpolate(method='linear')  # Interpolate missing values
        series = series.fillna(method='ffill')  # Forward fill any remaining NaNs
        series = series.fillna(method='bfill')  # Backward fill any remaining NaNs

    # Final check for NaN or inf
    if series.isna().sum() > 0 or np.isinf(series).sum() > 0:
        raise ValueError(f"Data cleaning failed for {name}: Still contains NaN or inf values")

    # Log transform to stabilize variance (add small constant to avoid log(0))
    series_log = np.log(series + 1e-6)

    return series, series_log

# Preprocess both series
short_close_full, short_close_log = preprocess_series(short_close_full, "COST 1min-2days")
long_close_full, long_close_log = preprocess_series(long_close_full, "COST 5min-5days")

# Check if the last value of short_close_full matches the original last value from the Excel file
current_short_last_value = short_close_full.iloc[-1]
print(f"\nCurrent last value of COST 1min-2days after processing: {current_short_last_value:.2f}")

if not np.isclose(current_short_last_value, original_short_last_value, rtol=1e-5, equal_nan=True):
    print("Mismatch detected! Restoring the original last value for COST 1min-2days...")
    short_close_full.iloc[-1] = original_short_last_value
    # Update log series accordingly
    short_close_log.iloc[-1] = np.log(original_short_last_value + 1e-6)
    print(f"Restored last value of COST 1min-2days: {short_close_full.iloc[-1]:.2f}")
else:
    print("Last value of COST 1min-2days matches the original Excel file value.")

# Function for unit root tests with interpretation
def unit_root_tests(series, name):
    print(f"\nUnit Root Tests for COST {name}:")

    # ADF Test
    adf_result = adfuller(series)
    print("ADF Test:")
    print(f'ADF Statistic: {adf_result[0]:.4f}')
    print(f'p-value: {adf_result[1]:.4f}')
    print(f'Critical Values: {adf_result[4]}')
    print("Interpretation:")
    if adf_result[1] < 0.05:
        print(f"  - p-value < 0.05: Reject null hypothesis - COST {name} is stationary")
    else:
        print(f"  - p-value >= 0.05: Fail to reject null - COST {name} may be non-stationary")

    # KPSS Test
    kpss_result = kpss(series)
    print("\nKPSS Test:")
    print(f'KPSS Statistic: {kpss_result[0]:.4f}')
    print(f'p-value: {kpss_result[1]:.4f}')
    print(f'Critical Values: {kpss_result[3]}')
    print("Interpretation:")
    if kpss_result[1] < 0.05:
        print(f"  - p-value < 0.05: Reject null hypothesis - COST {name} is non-stationary")
    else:
        print(f"  - p-value >= 0.05: Fail to reject null - COST {name} may be stationary")

# Perform unit root tests on the log-transformed data
unit_root_tests(short_close_log, "1min-2days (log)")
unit_root_tests(long_close_log, "5min-5days (log)")

# For cointegration test, we need both series to have the same length
min_length = min(len(short_close_log), len(long_close_log))
short_close_log_trimmed = short_close_log[:min_length]
long_close_log_trimmed = long_close_log[:min_length]
print(f"\nTrimmed both series to length {min_length} for cointegration test.")

# Cointegration test with interpretation
def cointegration_test(df):
    result = coint_johansen(df, det_order=0, k_ar_diff=1)
    print("\nJohansen Cointegration Test for COST (log-transformed):")
    print(f"Trace statistic: {result.lr1}")
    print(f"Critical values (90%, 95%, 99%): {result.cvt}")
    print("Interpretation:")
    for i in range(len(result.lr1)):
        if result.lr1[i] > result.cvt[i, 1]:
            print(f"  - r = {i}: Cointegration exists at 95% confidence level")
            print(f"    Trace statistic ({result.lr1[i]:.2f}) > 95% critical value ({result.cvt[i, 1]:.2f})")
        else:
            print(f"  - r = {i}: No cointegration at 95% confidence level")
            print(f"    Trace statistic ({result.lr1[i]:.2f}) <= 95% critical value ({result.cvt[i, 1]:.2f})")
    if result.lr1[0] > result.cvt[0, 1]:
        print("Conclusion: COST 1min-2days and 5min-5days are cointegrated - they share a long-run equilibrium relationship")
    else:
        print("Conclusion: No evidence of cointegration between COST 1min-2days and 5min-5days")

# Prepare data for cointegration
coint_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'COST_1min-2days': short_close_log_trimmed,
    'COST_5min-5days': long_close_log_trimmed
}).dropna()
cointegration_test(coint_df)

# Fit a simple ARIMA(1,1,1) model
def fit_arima(series, name, order=(1, 1, 1)):
    print(f"\nFitting ARIMA{order} model for COST {name}:")
    try:
        model = ARIMA(series, order=order)
        results = model.fit()
        print("Model fitted successfully.")
        return results
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error fitting ARIMA model for {name}: {e}")
        return None

# Fit ARIMA models on the log-transformed data
short_model = fit_arima(short_close_log, "1min-2days")
long_model = fit_arima(long_close_log, "5min-5days")

# Forecast next 30 periods (in log space)
forecast_steps = 30
short_forecast_log = short_model.forecast(steps=forecast_steps)
long_forecast_log = long_model.forecast(steps=forecast_steps)

# Transform forecasts back to original scale
short_forecast = np.exp(short_forecast_log) - 1e-6
long_forecast = np.exp(long_forecast_log) - 1e-6

# Constrain forecast to recent trend with a buffer
def constrain_forecast(forecast, historical_series, window=10, std_multiplier=2):
    recent_trend = historical_series.iloc[-window:].mean()
    recent_std = historical_series.iloc[-window:].std()
    forecast = np.clip(forecast,
                       recent_trend - std_multiplier * recent_std,
                       recent_trend + std_multiplier * recent_std)
    return forecast

# Apply constraints to forecasts
short_forecast = constrain_forecast(short_forecast, short_close_full)
long_forecast = constrain_forecast(long_forecast, long_close_full)

# Create forecast index for each series based on their full lengths
short_forecast_index = range(len(short_close_full), len(short_close_full) + forecast_steps)
long_forecast_index = range(len(long_close_full), len(long_close_full) + forecast_steps)

# Plot original series with forecasts (using original scale data)
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot(short_close_full, label='COST 1min-2days Historical')
plt.plot(short_forecast_index, short_forecast, label='COST 1min-2days Forecast', color='red')
plt.plot(long_close_full, label='COST 5min-5days Historical')
plt.plot(long_forecast_index, long_forecast, label='COST 5min-5days Forecast', color='green')
plt.title('COST Price Comparison: 1min-2days vs 5min-5days with Forecasts')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Detailed forecast plot with confidence intervals and interpretation
def plot_forecast(model, series, series_log, name, steps=30):
    forecast_obj = model.get_forecast(steps=steps)
    forecast_log = forecast_obj.predicted_mean
    conf_int_log = forecast_obj.conf_int()

    # Transform back to original scale
    forecast = np.exp(forecast_log) - 1e-6
    conf_int = np.exp(conf_int_log) - 1e-6

    # Constrain forecast and confidence intervals to recent trend
    forecast = constrain_forecast(forecast, series)
    conf_int = conf_int.apply(lambda x: constrain_forecast(x, series))

    forecast_index = range(len(series), len(series) + steps)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    plt.plot(series, label=f'COST {name} Historical')
    plt.plot(forecast_index, forecast, label='Forecast', color='red')
    plt.fill_between(forecast_index,
                    conf_int.iloc[:, 0],
                    conf_int.iloc[:, 1],
                    color='pink',
                    alpha=0.3,
                    label='95% Confidence Interval')
    plt.title(f'COST {name} Price Forecast')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    # Forecast interpretation
    last_value = series.iloc[-1]
    mean_forecast = forecast.mean()
    print(f"\nForecast Interpretation for COST {name}:")
    print(f"Last observed value: {last_value:.2f}")
    print(f"Average forecast value: {mean_forecast:.2f}")
    print(f"Forecast change: {mean_forecast - last_value:.2f}")
    if mean_forecast > last_value:
        print("Trend: Upward forecast trend")
    elif mean_forecast < last_value:
        print("Trend: Downward forecast trend")
    else:
        print("Trend: Flat forecast trend")
    print(f"95% CI range at period {steps}: [{conf_int.iloc[-1, 0]:.2f}, {conf_int.iloc[-1, 1]:.2f}]")

# Generate detailed forecast plots and interpretations
plot_forecast(short_model, short_close_full, short_close_log, "1min-2days")
plot_forecast(long_model, long_close_full, long_close_log, "5min-5days")

# Print forecast values
print("\nCOST 1min-2days Forecast Values (next 5 periods):")
print(short_forecast[:5])
print("\nCOST 5min-5days Forecast Values (next 5 periods):")
print(long_forecast[:5])

short_model = fit_arima(short_close_log, "1min-2days")
long_model = fit_arima(long_close_log, "5min-5days")

# Forecast next 30 periods (in log space)
forecast_steps = 30
short_forecast_log = short_model.forecast(steps=forecast_steps)
long_forecast_log = long_model.forecast(steps=forecast_steps)

# Transform forecasts back to original scale
short_forecast = np.exp(short_forecast_log) - 1e-6
long_forecast = np.exp(long_forecast_log) - 1e-6

# Constrain forecast to recent trend with a buffer
def constrain_forecast(forecast, historical_series, window=10, std_multiplier=2):
    recent_trend = historical_series.iloc[-window:].mean()
    recent_std = historical_series.iloc[-window:].std()
    forecast = np.clip(forecast,
                       recent_trend - std_multiplier * recent_std,
                       recent_trend + std_multiplier * recent_std)
    return forecast

# Apply constraints to forecasts
short_forecast = constrain_forecast(short_forecast, short_close_full)
long_forecast = constrain_forecast(long_forecast, long_close_full)

# Create forecast index for each series based on their full lengths
short_forecast_index = range(len(short_close_full), len(short_close_full) + forecast_steps)
long_forecast_index = range(len(long_close_full), len(long_close_full) + forecast_steps)

# Plot original series with forecasts (using original scale data)
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot(short_close_full, label='WMT 1min-2days Historical')
plt.plot(short_forecast_index, short_forecast, label='WMT 1min-2days Forecast', color='red')
plt.plot(long_close_full, label='WMT 5min-5days Historical')
plt.plot(long_forecast_index, long_forecast, label='WMT 5min-5days Forecast', color='green')
plt.title('WMT Price Comparison: 1min-2days vs 5min-5days with Forecasts')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Detailed forecast plot with confidence intervals and interpretation
def plot_forecast(model, series, series_log, name, steps=30):
    forecast_obj = model.get_forecast(steps=steps)
    forecast_log = forecast_obj.predicted_mean
    conf_int_log = forecast_obj.conf_int()

    # Transform back to original scale
    forecast = np.exp(forecast_log) - 1e-6
    conf_int = np.exp(conf_int_log) - 1e-6

    # Constrain forecast and confidence intervals to recent trend
    forecast = constrain_forecast(forecast, series)
    conf_int = conf_int.apply(lambda x: constrain_forecast(x, series))

    forecast_index = range(len(series), len(series) + steps)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    plt.plot(series, label=f'WMT {name} Historical')
    plt.plot(forecast_index, forecast, label='Forecast', color='red')
    plt.fill_between(forecast_index,
                    conf_int.iloc[:, 0],
                    conf_int.iloc[:, 1],
                    color='pink',
                    alpha=0.3,
                    label='95% Confidence Interval')
    plt.title(f'WMT {name} Price Forecast')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    # Forecast interpretation
    last_value = series.iloc[-1]
    mean_forecast = forecast.mean()
    print(f"\nForecast Interpretation for WMT {name}:")
    print(f"Last observed value: {last_value:.2f}")
    print(f"Average forecast value: {mean_forecast:.2f}")
    print(f"Forecast change: {mean_forecast - last_value:.2f}")
    if mean_forecast > last_value:
        print("Trend: Upward forecast trend")
    elif mean_forecast < last_value:
        print("Trend: Downward forecast trend")
    else:
        print("Trend: Flat forecast trend")
    print(f"95% CI range at period {steps}: [{conf_int.iloc[-1, 0]:.2f}, {conf_int.iloc[-1, 1]:.2f}]")

# Generate detailed forecast plots and interpretations
plot_forecast(short_model, short_close_full, short_close_log, "1min-2days")
plot_forecast(long_model, long_close_full, long_close_log, "5min-5days")

# Print forecast values
print("\nWMT 1min-2days Forecast Values (next 5 periods):")
print(short_forecast[:5])
print("\nWMT 5min-5days Forecast Values (next 5 periods):")
print(long_forecast[:5])

# Data cleaning: Check for NaN or inf values and handle them
def clean_series(series, name):
    print(f"\nChecking for NaN or inf values in {name}:")
    # Check for NaN values
    nan_count = series.isna().sum()
    print(f"Number of NaN values in {name}: {nan_count}")
    # Check for inf values
    inf_count = np.isinf(series).sum()
    print(f"Number of inf values in {name}: {inf_count}")

    # Replace inf with NaN for consistency
    series = series.replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)

    # Handle NaN values by interpolating, then forward/backward filling remaining NaNs
    if series.isna().sum() > 0:
        print(f"Handling NaN values in {name}...")
        series = series.interpolate(method='linear')  # Interpolate missing values
        series = series.fillna(method='ffill')  # Forward fill any remaining NaNs
        series = series.fillna(method='bfill')  # Backward fill any remaining NaNs

    # Final check
    if series.isna().sum() > 0 or np.isinf(series).sum() > 0:
        raise ValueError(f"Data cleaning failed for {name}: Still contains NaN or inf values")

    return series

# Clean both series (full data)

long_close_full = clean_series(long_close_full, "META 5min-5days")

# Function for unit root tests with interpretation
def unit_root_tests(series, name):
    print(f"\nUnit Root Tests for META {name}:")

    # ADF Test
    adf_result = adfuller(series)
    print("ADF Test:")
    print(f'ADF Statistic: {adf_result[0]:.4f}')
    print(f'p-value: {adf_result[1]:.4f}')
    print(f'Critical Values: {adf_result[4]}')
    print("Interpretation:")
    if adf_result[1] < 0.05:
        print(f"  - p-value < 0.05: Reject null hypothesis - META {name} is stationary")
    else:
        print(f"  - p-value >= 0.05: Fail to reject null - META {name} may be non-stationary")

    # KPSS Test
    kpss_result = kpss(series)
    print("\nKPSS Test:")
    print(f'KPSS Statistic: {kpss_result[0]:.4f}')
    print(f'p-value: {kpss_result[1]:.4f}')
    print(f'Critical Values: {kpss_result[3]}')
    print("Interpretation:")
    if kpss_result[1] < 0.05:
        print(f"  - p-value < 0.05: Reject null hypothesis - META {name} is non-stationary")
    else:
        print(f"  - p-value >= 0.05: Fail to reject null - META {name} may be stationary")

# Cointegration test with interpretation
def cointegration_test(df):
    result = coint_johansen(df, det_order=0, k_ar_diff=1)
    print("\nJohansen Cointegration Test for META:")
    print(f"Trace statistic: {result.lr1}")
    print(f"Critical values (90%, 95%, 99%): {result.cvt}")
    print("Interpretation:")
    for i in range(len(result.lr1)):
        if result.lr1[i] > result.cvt[i, 1]:
            print(f"  - r = {i}: Cointegration exists at 95% confidence level")
            print(f"    Trace statistic ({result.lr1[i]:.2f}) > 95% critical value ({result.cvt[i, 1]:.2f})")
        else:
            print(f"  - r = {i}: No cointegration at 95% confidence level")
            print(f"    Trace statistic ({result.lr1[i]:.2f}) <= 95% critical value ({result.cvt[i, 1]:.2f})")
    if result.lr1[0] > result.cvt[0, 1]:
        print("Conclusion: META 1min-2days and 5min-5days are cointegrated - they share a long-run equilibrium relationship")
    else:
        print("Conclusion: No evidence of cointegration between META 1min-2days and 5min-5days")

# Prepare data for cointegration

    'META_1min-2days': short_close,
    'META_5min-5days': long_close
}).dropna()
cointegration_test(coint_df)

# Function to find best ARIMA model with interpretation
def find_best_arima(series, name, max_p=3, max_d=2, max_q=3):
    best_aic = float('inf')
    best_order = None

    for p in range(max_p + 1):
        for d in range(max_d + 1):
            for q in range(max_q + 1):
                try:
                    model = ARIMA(series, order=(p, d, q))
                    results = model.fit()
                    if results.aic < best_aic:
                        best_aic = results.aic
                        best_order = (p, d, q)
                except:
                    continue

    print(f"\nBest ARIMA model for META {name}:")
    print(f"Order: {best_order}")
    print(f"AIC: {best_aic:.2f}")
    print("Interpretation:")
    print(f"  - p={best_order[0]}: {best_order[0]} autoregressive term(s)")
    print(f"  - d={best_order[1]}: {best_order[1]} difference(s) needed for stationarity")
    print(f"  - q={best_order[2]}: {best_order[2]} moving average term(s)")
    return best_order

# Find and fit best ARIMA models using the full data

long_order = find_best_arima(long_close_full, "5min-5days")
